The first lake effect snow event of the season brought very localized heavy wet snow to the immediate lake shore communities from Grand Haven and Ferrysburg south into far western Van Buren County. Accumulating snow only extended about 10-12 miles inland across western portions of Ottawa, Allegan, and Van Buren Counties. Most locations from Grand Haven south to South Haven received 2-3 inches of snow, but a nearly stationary snow band which developed over southwest Allegan County resulted in snow accumulations of 8-10 inches in both Glenn and Ganges, along and west of Interstate 196, in Ganges Township. The weight of the heavy, wet snow caused tree limbs to snap, which resulted in downed power lines around 7:00 AM in Ferrysburg and Spring Lake Township. Power loss affected 557 customers of Consumers Energy in that area. Snow reports included 2 inches in Holland and 1.5 inches in South Haven.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing drizzle made bridges and overpasses extremely slick. The deceased's Jeep hit an icy overpass on the Spiritwood interchange on I-94. The Jeep rolled numerous times down the embankment. The passenger was also injured in the accident.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first significant lake-effect snow of the 97-98 season brought heavy snow to the Keweenaw Peninsula and to North Central Upper Michigan. The snow began around 5 pm on Nov 9 and lasted into the evening of Nov 11.  Snow totals included Trimountain (10 SW of Houghton) 18.5 inches, Marquette County Airport 18 inches,  Phoenix (25 NE of Houghton) 16 inches, Redridge (10 W of Houghton) 14 inches and Eben (15 SW of Munising) 11 inches.

A cold front moved across western Lower Michigan during the early morning hours of November 12th, resulting in a lake-enhanced snow event which began late evening, Tuesday, November 11th. In general, 1 to 5 inches of snow fell across western and southern Lower Michigan, with 3 to 5 inch amounts confined to Lake, Ottawa, Kent, Allegan, Barry, Eaton, Ingham, and Kalamazoo Counties. The snow-covered and icy roads caught many overnight and early morning motorists by surprise. Slippery conditions are believed to have contributed to a seven-car pile-up on the northbound span of the U.S. 31 drawbridge late Tuesday night in Grand Haven. Two injuries were reported. The snow initially melted on road surfaces overnight, then froze early Wednesday morning as temperatures fell below freezing. This resulted in extremely icy conditions and an unusually high number of minor accidents, which included many slide-offs into ditches. Accidents with injuries were reported in Battle Creek, St. Joseph and Cass Counties, Hillsdale County (a rollover accident), and  Branch, Mecosta, Osceola, and Newaygo Counties. Snow reports included 5.0 inches in Grandville, 4.8 inches at the National Weather Service Office in southeast Grand Rapids, 4.5 inches in Hudsonville, 3.6-4.0 inches in Allegan, 3.2 inches in Hastings, 3.0 inches in Oshtemo, 3.0 inches in East Lansing, and 1.5 inches in Battle Creek.

In general, 1 to 5 inches of snow fell across western and southern Lower Michigan, with 3 to 5 inch amounts confined to Lake, Ottawa, Kent, Allegan, Barry, Eaton, Ingham, and Kalamazoo Counties. The snow-covered and icy roads caught many overnight and early morning motorists by surprise. Slippery conditions are believed to have contributed to a seven-car pile-up on the northbound span of the U.S. 31 drawbridge late Tuesday night in Grand Haven. Two injuries were reported. The snow initially melted on road surfaces overnight, then froze early Wednesday morning as temperatures fell below freezing. This resulted in extremely icy conditions and an unusually high number of minor accidents, which included many slide-offs into ditches. Accidents with injuries were reported in Battle Creek, St. Joseph and Cass Counties, Hillsdale County (a rollover accident), and  Branch, Mecosta, Osceola, and Newaygo Counties. Snow reports included 5.0 inches in Grandville, 4.8 inches at the National Weather Service Office in southeast Grand Rapids, 4.5 inches in Hudsonville, 3.6-4.0 inches in Allegan, 3.2 inches in Hastings, 3.0 inches in Oshtemo, 3.0 inches in East Lansing, and 1.5 inches in Battle Creek.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell in a band that extended into Burnett County from northeastern Minnesota. Grantsburg reported 7 inches of new snow.
Heavy snow fell in a band from Crow Wing to Pine Counties, Minnesota and extending into northwestern Wisconsin. Up to 7 inches of new snow was reported at Brainerd and Beroun.

A mixture of snow, sleet and freezing rain moved into portions of southeast Illinois late in the afternoon on November 13. Some glazing was reported in Lawrence County at the onset of the event. The activity changed over to all snow soon after the event began. A band of 3 to 5 inch snowfall occurred across this entire area. The event had tapered off by early morning on November 14.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The first winter storm of the season affected a very small portion of southern Illinois, mainly around Mt. Vernon. A mixture of rain, snow, and sleet changed to all snow. Accumulations of 4 to 5 inches occurred in much of Jefferson County, including Mount Vernon. Due to warm ground temperatures, most of the accumulation was on grassy areas, except for some slush on side roads. Further south,  minor icing occurred in the Marion-Carbondale area, but warm ground temperatures kept roads wet.
Between 1 to 2 inches of snow fell, followed by 0,5 inches of freezing rain.  Some power lines were downed.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system with abundant moisture moved from the gulf coastal states and into the Tennessee Valley spreading a wintry mix of precipitation into the region.  The low moved into East Central Ohio on the morning of November 14 and began to weaken.  The precipitation was primarily a mix of sleet and freezing rain.  Several inches fell along Interstate 80 in western Pennsylvania, where the precipitation fell primarily as sleet.  Several trees, large branches and power lines were downed throughout western Pennsylvania.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees and power lines were downed.  Up to 2 inches of a mixture of sleet and freezing rain fell.

Most of the precipitation fell in the form of freezing rain.  Dozens of small to medium sized limbs and several power lines were felled, some onto roadways, by the accumulating ice.  In Waynesboro (VAZ025), 1132 Virginia Power customers lost electricity.

CZ_NAME_STR: SOUTHERN EL PASO COUNTY/COLORADO SPRINGS AND VICINITY (ZONE)
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system combined with arctic air to bring widespread snowfall to south central and southeast Colorado, starting the evening of the 13th and lasting through the afternoon of the 14th. Snowfall accumulations ranged from 6 to 12 inches across the mountains and high valleys, with 4 to 8 inches across the foothills and nearby plains.  The heaviest amounts occurred in the southern Sangre de Cristo mountains where up to 12 inches fell around Cuchara and Stonewall.  A narrow band of intense snow fell near Del Norte in the San Luis Valley, bringing up to 10 inches.

With a high pressure system extending from northwest of the Great Lakes east-southeast across Northern New England, a low pressure system developed off the Carolina Coast during Thursday evening on November 13th.  It slowly intensified as it moved northeast, passing south of Long Island during Friday afternoon before moving offshore during Friday evening.

A mixture of snow, sleet, and freezing rain created hazardous weather conditions across the area.  Precipitation accumulated on roads, making both driving and walking hazardous.  Several, mostly minor, traffic accidents occurred.  Freezing rain also accumulated on trees, causing some tree limbs to fall on power lines that resulted in scattered power outages.

A strong low pressure system produced snow and blowing snow creating near whiteout conditions at times.  Six inches of snow fell in the Sisseton foot hills by Friday evening in Roberts and eastern Marshall counties.  Strong north winds gusting to near 35 mph and snow produced visibilities below 1/2 mile at times over a large portion of northeast South Dakota Thursday evening into Friday.  Classes  were cancelled around Summit because of near whiteout conditions while, classes were delayed for two hours in Britton.  I-29 was closed just north of the Grant County line for a time after a semi-trailer rollover  early Thursday evening.

A coastal storm or nor'easter developed along the South Carolina coast the morning of the 13th and moved slowly northeast and was about 75 miles east of Salisbury Maryland at 7 a.m. EST on the 14th.  The low pressure system then accelerated and was well southeast of Nova Scotia on the morning of the 15th.  Preceding this low pressure system was an unseasonably cold and dry air mass.  This factor coupled with the northeast flow around the coastal low and the presence of a new and fresh supply of cold air supplied by another high pressure system in nearby Canada kept temperatures near the ground at or below the freezing mark.  Thus precipitation fell as mainly freezing rain.  The freezing rain caused power outages and contributed to three fatalities involving motor vehicles.

Precipitation started during the late evening on the 13th and lasted about 24 hours ending as a period of light snow across much of the area, especially in the Poconos where 1 to 3 inches accumulated on top of the ice.  In Upper Bucks County,  freezing rain fell during the morning of the 14th, before most locations rose above the freezing mark.  Some pockets of freezing formed again that evening before the precipitation ended.  The ground was still relatively warm and ice accrued mainly on power lines, tree limbs, bridges and overpasses.  A 38 year-old Allentown woman was killed at 140 a.m. EST on the 14th when she lost control of her car.  At 9 p.m. EST on the 14th a 51-year-old man and his 17-year-old son were killed when they lost control of their car on the Northeast Extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike in Kidder Township (Carbon County) and were broadsided by a tractor trailer.  The Pennsylvania State Police division in the Poconos advised against nonessential travel because of numerous reports of fender benders and vehicles sliding off roadways.

As the freezing rain continued to accrue on trees and power lines (about one-half to three-quarters of an inch of ice accrued on most surfaces), they started to come down.  Pennsylvania Power and Light reported about 50,000 homes and businesses lost power in their northeast Pennsylvania service area.  It took about 24 hours to bring the last 5,000 customers back on line.  In Lehigh County, there were numerous outages on the east and south side of Allentown and also in South Whitehall Township.  The greatest accretion of ice occurred in the northeast part of the county.  In Northampton County numerous outages were reported in Bethlehem and three vehicles were damaged by fallen limbs.  Few neighborhoods were spared tree damage.  The most ice though accrued in the northwest part of the county around Danielsville.  In Berks County, the greatest ice accretion and most of the fallen limbs were reported from Oley northeast to the Blue Mountains.

At 9 p.m. EST on the 14th a 51-year-old man and his 17-year-old son were killed when they lost control of their car on the Northeast Extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike in Kidder Township (Carbon County) and were broadsided by a tractor trailer.  The Pennsylvania State Police division in the Poconos advised against nonessential travel because of numerous reports of fender benders and vehicles sliding off roadways.

As the freezing rain continued to accrue on trees and power lines (about one-half to three-quarters of an inch of ice accrued on most surfaces), they started to come down.  Pennsylvania Power and Light reported about 50,000 homes and businesses lost power in their northeast Pennsylvania service area.  It took about 24 hours to bring the last 5,000 customers back on line.  In Lehigh County, there were numerous outages on the east and south side of Allentown and also in South Whitehall Township.  The greatest accretion of ice occurred in the northeast part of the county.  In Northampton County numerous outages were reported in Bethlehem and three vehicles were damaged by fallen limbs.  Few neighborhoods were spared tree damage.  The most ice though accrued in the northwest part of the county around Danielsville.  In Berks County, the greatest ice accretion and most of the fallen limbs were reported from Oley northeast to the Blue Mountains.

A coastal storm or nor'easter developed along the South Carolina coast the morning of the 13th and moved slowly northeast and was about 75 miles east of Salisbury Maryland at 7 a.m. EST on the 14th.  The low pressure system then accelerated and was well southeast of Nova Scotia on the morning of the 15th.  Preceding this low pressure system was an unseasonably cold and dry air mass.  This factor coupled with the northeast flow around the coastal low and the presence of a new and fresh supply of cold air supplied by another high pressure system in nearby Canada kept temperatures near the ground at or below the freezing mark.  Thus precipitation fell as mainly freezing rain.  The freezing rain caused power outages and contributed to three fatalities involving motor vehicles.

Precipitation started during the late evening on the 13th and lasted about 24 hours ending as a period of light snow across much of the area, especially in the Poconos where 1 to 3 inches accumulated on top of the ice.  In Upper Bucks County,  freezing rain fell during the morning of the 14th, before most locations rose above the freezing mark.  Some pockets of freezing formed again that evening before the precipitation ended.  The ground was still relatively warm and ice accrued mainly on power lines, tree limbs, bridges and overpasses. A complex storm system, with its main center having tracked up the coast from Virginia to New England, brought a period of heavy wet snow to much of central New York from just after midnight on the 14th until late that same evening.  
     Amounts were heaviest from portions of the central southern tier across the Finger Lakes region and into the Mohawk Valley.  There were many localities within this area that received over a foot of snow from this event.  Some of the highest totals follow:  Auburn (Cayuga county) - 16 inches, Burdett (Schuyler county) - 14 inches, Holland Patent (Oneida county) - 13 inches, Reading Centre (Schuyler county) - 12 inches, and Haskinville (Steuben county) - 12 inches.  Snow loading from the heavy wet nature of the snowfall resulted in downed power lines and isolated roof collapses in sections of Onondaga and Oneida counties.  
     A broader area of 6 to 10 inch accumulations affected most of the central southern tier and Susquehanna regions across New York's southern tier.

Localized heavy snow of 6 to 6.5 inches fell in the Lake Geneva (Walworth Co.) and other locations southeast of Lake Geneva as a low pressure system moved east across northern Illinois.  Snow also fell over the entire southern third of Wisconsin with most accumulations in the 2 to 4 inch range.  The western parts of Kenosha and Racine counties picked up 5.5 inches.  Dozens of motor vehicle accidents were reported due to slippery roads.

On November 13 and 14, a winter storm tracked from the southeast coast north to the coast of southern New England and then out to sea.  Heavy snow fell across much of eastern New York with the greatest accumulations observed over the Mohawk Valley, Capital District and southern Adirondacks.  In the southern Catskills, mid Hudson Valley and southern Taconics, heavy accumulations of sleet and freezing rain occurred after several inches of snow.  In this region the freezing rain produced scattered power outages.  In the Village of New Paltz in Ulster County, approximately 2,000 customers lost power including the State University College at New Paltz.  Some specific snowfall totals included: 8 inches at Albany, 14 inches at Salisbury in Herkimer County, 11 inches at Saratoga Springs in Saratoga County, 8 inches at Cobleskill in Schoharie County,  11 inches at Caroga Lake in Fulton County and 9 inches at Grannville in Washington County.

Heavy snow fell across much of eastern New York with the greatest accumulations observed over the Mohawk Valley, Capital District and southern Adirondacks.  In the southern Catskills, mid Hudson Valley and southern Taconics, heavy accumulations of sleet and freezing rain occurred after several inches of snow.  In this region the freezing rain produced scattered power outages.  In the Village of New Paltz in Ulster County, approximately 2,000 customers lost power including the State University College at New Paltz.  Some specific snowfall totals included: 8 inches at Albany, 14 inches at Salisbury in Herkimer County, 11 inches at Saratoga Springs in Saratoga County, 8 inches at Cobleskill in Schoharie County,  11 inches at Caroga Lake in Fulton County and 9 inches at Grannville in Washington County.

One quarter to one half inch of freezing rain accumulated on roads and other surfaces along with three to five inches of snow, causing slippery roads and hazardous driving conditions.  Several traffic accidents were reported, with a 30 car pile-up occurring in Edinboro (Southern Erie County).

A coastal storm or nor'easter developed along the South Carolina coast the morning of the 13th and moved slowly northeast and was about 75 miles east of Salisbury Maryland at 7 a.m. EST on the 14th.  The low pressure system then accelerated and was well southeast of Nova Scotia on the morning of the 15th.  Preceding this low pressure was an unseasonably cold and dry air mass.  This factor coupled with the northeast flow around the coastal low and the presence of a new and fresh supply of cold air supplied by another high pressure system in nearby Canada kept temperatures near the ground at or below the freezing mark and caused precipitation to fall as mainly freezing rain in Sussex County,  in northern areas of Warren County and northwest sections of Morris County.  The freezing rain contributed to a fatal accident in Sussex County as a 49-year-old man was killed at 147 p.m. EST when he lost control of his car and slammed into a utility pole on U.S. Route 206 in Sandyston Township.

Precipitation started around midnight on the 14th and lasted most of the day.  Precipitation ended as some light snow across much of the area, especially in Sussex County where 1 to 3 inches accumulated on top of the ice in the northwest hills.  Across Hunterdon, Middlesex and Somerset Counties, precipitation started briefly as freezing rain before going over to plain rain.  The rain then change back to freezing rain across northern parts of the counties before it ended late on the 14th. 

Ice accretions averaged around half an inch, but reached close to one inch in the northwest corner of Sussex County.  The ice brought down tree limbs and power lines and caused power outages to 2,000 customers across Northwest New Jersey.  A downed tree in Randolph Township (Morris County) caused the greatest concentration of outages in one area.   The freezing rain contributed to numerous accidents across Northwest New Jersey.  In Newton (Sussex County) alone twice vehicles were involved in head-on collisions after they slid into oncoming traffic.  In Morris County, a Morris Township bus driver fractured both legs after the bus slid off a driveway into a tree.  Two children were also injured.  In Denville, a car slid into a guide wire, while in Parsippany, a van flipped onto its roof.

A strong storm moved north from the Aleutian Islands to 150 miles west of Saint Mathew Island in the central Bering Sea. The storm produced Blizzard Conditions at Gambell and Savoonga on St. Lawrence Island, as well as High Hinds at the same locations. Observations from Tin City were not available during the event.  Max Winds : Gambell 49 kt Sustained, 59kt gust; Savvonga 46 kt sustained, 50 kt gust.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Chadron State Park received 6 inches of snow; snow and blowing snow reduced visibilities to near zero on Highway 285 south of Chadron through Chadron State Park.

The first winter storm of the season began overnight on Thursday, November 13th, and produced a wintery mix of snow, sleet, and freezing rain across most of central Pennsylvania. Low pressure moved northeast from the Mississippi Valley, creating an easterly flow of moisture inland from the Atlantic. Warm air moved in atop cold air trapped on the surface. Nearly an inch of precipitation fell across the area, but only the northern tier counties recorded heavy snow. Up to 6 inches fell in Russell in Warren County and 5.5 inches fell in LaPorte in Sullivan County. In other areas, much of the precipitation fell as heavy sleet or freezing rain. There were many traffic accidents across the region as roads iced up from the heavy sleet and freezing rain. Heavier snow fell to the north across much of western New York.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed off the mid-Atlantic coast and moved over the Atlantic Ocean southeast of Cape Cod.  This weather system produced the first important nor'easter of the season for much of the state.  Snow changed to rain along the coast, especially from Boston southward and over southeastern Massachusetts, but elsewhere there was an accumulation of several inches of snow before a change to rain.  Boston had 3.7 inches and Worcester had 5.0 inches.  The heaviest snowfalls occurred over parts of Middlesex and Essex Counties.  Newburyport, E. Woburn, and N. Woburn all reported 6 inches.  The snowfall caused numerous fender-bender accidents and several tie-ups on interstate highways.

An early season winter storm brought heavy snow to the area as low pressure moved north along the Atlantic coast. Snowfall amounts ranged from six to twelve inches across the region with the highest amounts over the Genesee valley and western Finger Lakes. The snow  was wet and heavy and snarled traffic badly. Countless accidents were reported, many with injuries. Several school districts were forced to close. A record 9.5 inches fell at the Buffalo-Niagara Airport. At Rochester, the 10.6 inches that fell also established a record for the date. Some of the highest reports of heavy, wet snow  included 10-12 inches at West Seneca, Colden, Darien Center, Bennington, Portageville, Henrietta, Mount Morris and Springwater.

A strong low pressure produced 3 to 5 inches of snow across the Northeast Nebraska Panhandle and Northcentral Nebraska.  Northwest winds at 25 to 40 mph with some stronger gusts produced blowing and drifing of snow and visibilities down to zero at times.  The strong winds and temperatures around 20 degrees produced wind chill values ranging from 15 to 25 below zero.  The winter weather caused some school closings and cancellation of activities.

A strong low pressure produced 3 to 5 inches of snow across the Northeast Nebraska Panhandle and Northcentral Nebraska.  Northwest winds at 25 to 40 mph with some stronger gusts produced blowing and drifing of snow and visibilities down to zero at times.  The strong winds and temperatures around 20 degrees produced wind chill values ranging from 15 to 25 below zero.  The winter weather caused some school closings and cancellation of activities.

An early season winter storm brought heavy snow to the area as low pressure moved north along the Atlantic coast. Snowfall amounts ranged from six to twelve inches across the region with the highest amounts over the Genesee valley and western Finger Lakes. The snow  was wet and heavy and snarled traffic badly. Countless accidents were reported, many with injuries. Several school districts were forced to close. A record 9.5 inches fell at the Buffalo-Niagara Airport. At Rochester, the 10.6 inches that fell also established a record for the date. Some of the highest reports of heavy, wet snow  included 10-12 inches at West Seneca, Colden, Darien Center, Bennington, Portageville, Henrietta, Mount Morris and Springwater.

Cold air spilled south into Iowa as a cold polar vortex aloft dropped south into the state.  Snow fell for an extended period of snow occurred, however much of it fell during the late afternoon and evening hours of the 14th into the early morning hours of the 15th.  All of the state received snow with the heaviest over the northeast half of the state.  Amounts greater than six inches occurred over the north central counties, extending into the Waterloo area.  The heaviest snowfall report came from Butler County, where an observer in Allison reported 12 inches of snow.  Most of the snow in the heavy snow area was in the 6 to 7 inch range however.  Travel was difficult due to blowing snow and the fact that the snow initially melted on road surfaces and then froze.  Winds were generally in the 15 to 30 MPH range through the storm, causing greatly reduced visibilities in open areas.

CZ_NAME_STR: CENTRAL HIGH PLAINS/ESTANCIA VALLEY COUNTY / SE SANTA FE / W SAN MIGUEL / TORRANCE EXCEPT X W / E SOCORRO (ZONE)
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A heavy, wet snow across northcentral New Mexico turned into a sudden ice pack that caused treacherous driving, especially along sections of Interstate Highways 25 and 40 mainly north and east of Albuquerque. Despite a sudden rash of accidents which closed the Interstates south of Santa Fe and east of Moriarty, no serious injuries were reported. Mountain ski areas from Red River and Taos south to Sandia Crest measured 12 to 15 inches of fresh powder snow.

An upper level storm system combined with arctic air to bring widespread snowfall to south central and southeast Colorado, starting the evening of the 13th and lasting through the afternoon of the 14th. Snowfall accumulations ranged from 6 to 12 inches across the mountains and high valleys, with 4 to 8 inches across the foothills and nearby plains.  The heaviest amounts occurred in the southern Sangre de Cristo mountains where up to 12 inches fell around Cuchara and Stonewall.  A narrow band of intense snow fell near Del Norte in the San Luis Valley, bringing up to 10 inches.

An early season winter storm brought heavy snow to the area as low pressure moved north along the Atlantic coast. Snowfall amounts ranged from six to twelve inches across the region with the highest amounts over the Genesee valley and western Finger Lakes. The snow  was wet and heavy and snarled traffic badly. Countless accidents were reported, many with injuries. Several school districts were forced to close. A record 9.5 inches fell at the Buffalo-Niagara Airport. At Rochester, the 10.6 inches that fell also established a record for the date. Some of the highest reports of heavy, wet snow  included 10-12 inches at West Seneca, Colden, Darien Center, Bennington, Portageville, Henrietta, Mount Morris and Springwater.

A coastal storm or nor'easter developed along the South Carolina coast the morning of the 13th and moved slowly northeast and was about 75 miles east of Salisbury Maryland at 7 a.m. EST on the 14th.  The low pressure system then accelerated and was well southeast of Nova Scotia on the morning of the 15th.  Preceding this low pressure was an unseasonably cold and dry air mass.  This factor coupled with the northeast flow around the coastal low and the presence of a new and fresh supply of cold air supplied by another high pressure system in nearby Canada kept temperatures near the ground at or below the freezing mark and caused precipitation to fall as mainly freezing rain in Sussex County,  in northern areas of Warren County and northwest sections of Morris County.  The freezing rain contributed to a fatal accident in Sussex County as a 49-year-old man was killed at 147 p.m. EST when he lost control of his car and slammed into a utility pole on U.S. Route 206 in Sandyston Township.

Precipitation started around midnight on the 14th and lasted most of the day.  Precipitation ended as some light snow across much of the area, especially in Sussex County where 1 to 3 inches accumulated on top of the ice in the northwest hills.  Across Hunterdon, Middlesex and Somerset Counties, precipitation started briefly as freezing rain before going over to plain rain.  The rain then change back to freezing rain across northern parts of the counties before it ended late on the 14th. 

Ice accretions averaged around half an inch, but reached close to one inch in the northwest corner of Sussex County.  The ice brought down tree limbs and power lines and caused power outages to 2,000 customers across Northwest New Jersey.  A downed tree in Randolph Township (Morris County) caused the greatest concentration of outages in one area.   The freezing rain contributed to numerous accidents across Northwest New Jersey.  In Newton (Sussex County) alone twice vehicles were involved in head-on collisions after they slid into oncoming traffic.  In Morris County, a Morris Township bus driver fractured both legs after the bus slid off a driveway into a tree.  Two children were also injured.  In Denville, a car slid into a guide wire, while in Parsippany, a van flipped onto its roof.

Low pressure tracked from Iowa early on the 15th, across the Michigan, Ohio, and Indiana borders, to Lake Ontario early on the morning of the 16th.  Light snow fell across southern lower Michigan with snow fall accumulations of 1 to 4 inches.  However, cold north and northeast winds off of the relatively warmer waters of Lake Huron enhanced the snowfall amounts in eastern Sanilac and northeast St. Clair counties where accumulations were generally 4 to 8 inches.  Port Sanilac received 8 inches of snowfall, but Sheriff Departments reported localized areas of eastern Sanilac county received up to 12 inches.

An intense band of lake effect snow developed down the length of eastern Lake Michigan in a north wind flow and resulted in snow accumulations of 6 to 18 inches across far western Van Buren County and most of Berrien County. As the wind flow turned slightly more northwest during the morning hours of Sunday, November 16th, lake effect snow bands moved further inland across western Ottawa, western Allegan, central Van Buren, and Cass Counties. Snow totals in these areas ranged from 2 to 5 inches by the time the lake effect diminished. The worst conditions were felt across southwest Berrien County, where storm accumulations reached 18 inches in the New Buffalo-Sawyer areas. The weight of the heavy, wet snow downed tree limbs and power lines which cut power to 3,000 American Electric Power customers in southwest Berrien County. Snow reports included 13 inches in Baroda, 12 inches in St. Joseph and Coloma, 11 inches in Buchanan, 10 inches in Stevensville, 6 inches in South Haven, 4.7 inches in Holland, and 4.5 inches in Fennville.

Heavy lake effect snow accumulated an average of six to eight inches.  Locally heavier amounts were 10 inches at Hambden and 12 inches each at Chardon and Thompson (all in Geauga County), and 10 inches at Conneaut (Ashtabula).

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing drizzle fell across parts of South Central North Dakota most of the afternoon. The deceased was driving a pickup eastbound on I-94 when he lost control of the vehicle and crossed them median hitting a suburban head on. All 8 people in the suburban suffered minor injuries. The deceased's wife was also injured. Within a 6 mile stretch of I-94 that included this accident, there were 2 other accidents all within 10 minutes of each other resulting in 3 minor injuries. Traffic speeds were reported to be around 20 mph during the time of the accidents.

A strong low pressure system moved east across Lake Superior on the 22nd bringing cold air over the relatively warmer waters of Lake Superior. This produced heavy lake-effect snow in areas favored by northwest winds that lasted into the morning of the 24th.  The heaviest snows occurred between Ironwood  and the Keweenaw Peninsula and between Munising and Grand Marais.  The highest snow total was Trimountain (10 SW of Houghton) with 21.0 inches.

Snow totals included:
Alger County                                   Baraga County                    Gogebic County
Melstrand        15.3 inches             Herman      12.0 inches       Ramsay      15.5 inches
Shingleton      14.0  inches            Baraga       11.5 inches 
Munising         13.3 inches
Grand Marais   10.2 inches

Houghton County                        Keweenaw County                      Ontonagon County
Trimountain    21.0 inches           Phoenix        18.0 inches           Bergland          15.0 inches
Houghton        18.6 inches                                                             Ontonagon      12.5 inches
Hancock          18.4 inches

A low pressure system south of Long Island on November 22, produced heavy wet snow across southern Vermont.  Snowfall averaged 4 to 8 inches in Bennington and Windham Counties.  The heavy wet snow downed trees and power lines, which produced scattered power outages.  The power outages were most widespread in Windham County.  Snowfall reached 7 inches at Putney in Windham County and 8 inches at Woodford in Bennington County.

Southern parts of the state received little or no accumulation while the north and mountains got several inches.

Low pressure south of James Bay produced a brisk, relatively cold flow across Lakes Erie and Ontario. Lake effect snow squalls resulted in significantly reduced visibilities and localized amounts of six to twelve inches. Several automobile accidents were blamed on the treacherous road conditions. Specific amounts reported:  Parish 11; Springville 10" ; and Jamestown and Perrysburg 7"."

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific storm brought heavy rain...thunderstorms and snow to Southern California. With this storm, snow levels dropped to around 5000 feet. Snow accumulations up to 6 inches were reported in the mountains. At lower elevations, heavy rain and small hail fell. Rainfall totals ranged from 0.50 to 1.50 inches across the coast...up to 4.00 inches in the mountains. The heavy rain produced numerous street flooding. In Alhambra, 5 high school students were swept down a wash by storm runoff. Three students died while two others survived.
